quran[21]{c,v,t,f}:
51,31,"Abraham said: “Envoys (of Allah), what is your errand?” {1}",footnotes:1:As the angels come in human guise only on highly important occasions
51,32,"They replied: “Behold, we have been sent to a wicked people {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,33,"that we may unleash a shower of clay-stones"
51,34,"marked by your Lord upon those who go beyond the limits.” {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,35,"Then {1} We evacuated there from all the believers",footnotes:1:As to what happened between them and the people of the Prophet Lot (peace be upon him) when the angels reached his house after their meeting with the Prophet Abraham (peace be upon them)
51,36,"– and We did not find there any, apart from a single house of Muslims {1} –",footnotes:1:That is
51,37,"and We left therein a Sign for those who fear the grievous chastisement. {1}",footnotes:1:A sign: the Dead Sea
51,38,"There is also a Sign for you in the story of Moses when We sent him with a clear authority to Pharaoh. {1}",footnotes:1:A clear authority: such miracles and clear evidences which made it absolutely manifest that he had been appointed as a Messenger by the Creator of the earth and heavens.
51,39,"But Pharaoh turned away, showing arrogance on account of his power, and said (about Moses): “He is either a sorcerer or a madman.” {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,40,"So We seized him and his hosts, and cast them into the sea. He became an object of much blame. {1}",footnotes:1:A whole history has been compressed into this brief sentence. To understand it well one should know that Pharaoh was the absolute ruler of the greatest center of civilization and culture of the world in those days and the people of the adjoining lands were overawed by his power and might. Obviously
51,41,"There is also a Sign for you in (the story of) Ad, when We let loose upon them an ominous wind"
51,42,"that left nothing that it came upon without reducing it to rubble. {1}",footnotes:1:The word used for this wind is aqim
51,43,"There is also a Sign for you in (the story of) Thamud. They were told: “Enjoy yourselves for a while.” {1}",footnotes:1:The commentators have disputed as to which respite it implies. Qatadah says that it alludes to that verse of Surah Houd in which it has been stated that when the Thamud killed the she camel of the Prophet Salih (peace be upon him)
51,44,"But they brazenly disobeyed their Lord’s command, and then a sudden chastisement {1} overtook them while they looked on.",footnotes:1:Different words have been used for this torment at different places in the Quran. Somewhere it has been called rajafah (a frightful and shocking calamity)
51,45,"They were unable even to stand up or protect themselves. {1}",footnotes:1:Intisar from which the word muntasirun in the original is derived means to save oneself from an attack by somebody as well as to avenge oneself on the attacker.
51,46,"Before all these We destroyed the people of Noah: they were a wicked people."
51,47,"And heaven – We {1} made it with Our Own Power and We have the Power to do so. {2}",footnotes:1:After presenting historical arguments for the Hereafter
51,48,"And the earth – We spread it out, and how well have We smoothed it! {1}",footnotes:1:For explanation
51,49,"And of everything We have created pairs; {1} perhaps you will take heed. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
51,50,"Flee, therefore, to Allah. Surely I am a clear warner to you from Him;"
51,51,"and do not set up any deity with Allah. Surely I am a clear warner to you from Him. {1}",footnotes:1:Though these sentences are the Word of Allah
